values ('345bcb82c4bf81afb8c8dedec2007ade', 'lisakleyn', 'Lisa', 'Kleyn', 'lisamkleyn@gmail.com', '+44 7492277234', 'April 17, 2026 11:52 AM', '[{"label":"Who will need to be included in communication about the work we’re doing?","value":"Zach Taylor: ztaylorwell@gmail.com"},{"label":"Accounting Contact","value":"N/A"},{"label":"Who is your IDEAL target customer?","value":"High-functioning adults and couples, typically between 25 and 55, who have built meaningful lives but find themselves failing at the relationships that matter most to them. They are not struggling because they lack intelligence, emotional awareness, or effort. They are struggling because nobody ever taught them the fundamental skills of loving and repairing well. They know something is wrong but may not be able to externalize the pattern find themselves blaming themselves or their partner. Some of them may be able to name the pattern or know how to repair but knowing has not been enough to change it, and that gap between understanding and doing is exactly where I work."},{"label":"Do you have any brand identity or guidelines that you have available for reference? If so, please share the link below:","value":"https://drive.google.com/file/d/1EeGe-wrDfpD15DstD4SWacpQKWmNGEpG/view?usp=share_link"},{"label":"What are the PAIN points of the customers you help?","value":"They are caught in the same cycles, repeating the same arguments, having the same ruptures, and genuinely cannot understand why, despite wanting things to be different. They push away the very connection they are most desperate for. In moments of emotional threat the nervous system takes over and they say things they do not mean, shut down when they want to stay present, or pursue in ways that drive their partner further away.\n\nWhat makes this particularly painful is the shame that follows. They know they reacted. They know it was not their best self. And they have no reliable way to interrupt it before it happens again.\n\nUnderneath all of this, most carry relational wounds from early attachment experiences that were never meant to harm them. Parents who were doing their best. Families who loved them but could not model what secure love looks like. The accumulation of that, over years and across relationships, is what I call relational and attachment trauma, and it lives not in the mind but in the body and nervous system. That is why talk alone has not been enough.\n\nThere is also a third force at work that almost nobody in this field talks about: their social network. The people who love them most, friends, family, a trusted sister or closest friend, are quietly shaping the quality of their relationship every single day. When things get hard, those people take their side. They validate their feelings, they affirm that their partner is wrong, because that is what love looks like. But it is eroding the relationship from the outside in, and my clients have no framework for understanding or addressing it."},{"label":"What are the DESIRED OUTCOMES of the customers you help?","value":"They want to feel secure in their capacity to overcome sabotaging patterns and to find their way back to greater relationship satisfaction. They should feel more confident in knowing what keeps them stuck, clear on what triggers their patterns, and equipped with exactly what to do to find their way back to solid ground together.\nMore specifically: they want to be able to stay regulated in the moments that used to overwhelm them. They want conflict to feel survivable and repairable rather than catastrophic. They want to understand their own attachment history with compassion rather than shame, and they want their partner to understand it too. They want a shared language, a shared framework, a shared way of returning to each other after rupture.\nSome come wanting clarity rather than repair. Whether to stay or to leave, but to make that decision from a grounded, honest place rather than from exhaustion or fear. That is an equally valid and important outcome, and my work holds space for both.\nAt the deepest level, what they are seeking is the experience of moving from survival patterns to secure love. That is the shift I am in the business of creating."},{"label":"What is your PROCESS for helping clients get from where they are to where they want to go?","value":"I use The SECURE Method™, a trauma-informed, evidence-based, systems-focused method I developed across more than a decade of clinical work and doctoral research at the Universities of Oxford and Cape Town. It draws on attachment theory, polyvagal science, Internal Family Systems, Emotionally Focused Therapy, Acceptance and Commitment Therapy, and somatic co-regulation approaches. Not as a menu of techniques but as an integrated system.\nThe method has six stages. Sensing the early signal of a trigger before it takes hold. Externalising the pattern so that partners stop seeing each other as the problem and start seeing the cycle as the thing to address together. Co-regulating the nervous system before attempting any repair conversation, because no meaningful communication happens in a dysregulated body. Unblending from the reactive protective part so that responses come from the grounded self rather than the frightened one. Repairing with intention after rupture, in a way that actually rebuilds trust rather than just smoothing things over. And over time, earning a new secure baseline, not one that was inherited or assumed, but one that was genuinely built.\nThe reason this works when other approaches have not is that it operates at the level where the reactions actually happen. Not at the level of language or strategy, but at the level of the nervous system, the body, and the attachment system. That is where the patterns live. That is where the change has to happen."},{"label":"Please provide links to some examples of social media clips that you like from a design perspective:","value":"I like the use of zoom, angles, b-roll, background music... https://www.instagram.com/reel/DPrT6yjjRje/?igsh=MWIyeXNvMTdhZ3c3OA==\nI also like the references to a culturally relevant movie/show...\nhttps://www.instagram.com/reel/DWl421bDnoT/?igsh=NTc4MTIwNjQ2YQ==\n\nI like these reaction videos: https://www.instagram.com/reel/DVj5k8MFR0q/?igsh=MWVlb3BmdDlzcDIwYg==\n\nI also like videos with a physical hook: https://www.instagram.com/reel/DXCrAHDisKf/?igsh=N3U0NXI3Zmp4b2M3\n\nhttps://www.instagram.com/p/DVKZBdxDlO-/\n\nHere are examples of video''s I would like to react to:\n1. https://www.instagram.com/reel/DM-XpNJvWKR/?igsh=dDBubmdlMXlpMWJ5\n2. https://www.instagram.com/reel/DNTfpfMuPK_/?igsh=MTQxYWoybmhmMTNlbg==\n3. https://www.instagram.com/reel/DPcfoLiEikj/?igsh=MW44OXZ0eGhvMzYwcg=="},{"label":"Please provide links to video thumbnails/cover images that you like from a design perspective:","value":"https://www.instagram.com/reel/DRIFWqUiYpv/?igsh=MXQxNWw1cmc1aGJ6dQ==\n\nhttps://www.instagram.com/reel/DTifm10Ex__/?igsh=OGRzOHBtMzF6MWJv\n\nhttps://www.instagram.com/reel/DVt_yZcigxa/?igsh=MWRwNDc0N3pmem40YQ=="},{"label":"What font preferences do you have or would you like to see in your designs? If you are open to our recommendations, please feel free to mention it below:","value":"I like this font but am open to suggestions: https://www.instagram.com/reel/DPcfoLiEikj/?igsh=MW44OXZ0eGhvMzYwcg=="},{"label":"What color preferences do you have or would you like to see in your designs?","value":"white and a butter yellow accent color: https://www.instagram.com/reel/DXJzhsahTIC/?igsh=MTF3enR3Z2w3bmUyZQ==\n\nhttps://www.instagram.com/reel/DBTu5mYgkP_/?igsh=MWpsdzNmNzJ6eWJlag==\n\nhttps://www.instagram.com/reel/DBgf36TS5ss/?igsh=N3ltb2FnMnNhZzQz\n\nMaybe also withe some coral red as shown in the brand kit..."},{"label":"Google Drive Link to pictures of yourself","value":"https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1dRle1bGbfVJXkR5WJHlLDiJhlBcefQY3?usp=share_link"},{"label":"What would success look like working together?","value":"I have an ambitious vision and I would love to partner with you to make it real. I come into this knowing it will take serious work on both sides, and I am genuinely excited to hear how you think we get there.\n\nAt the heart of everything is a mission I care about deeply. I want to change the statistic on preventable divorce and relational trauma. The way I do that is by teaching people what most of us were never taught: how relational trauma accumulates and gets inherited across generations, how our social networks shape our relationships in ways we cannot see, how the nervous system drives our most destructive patterns, how to unblend from reactive parts and respond from a grounded self, and what secure love and genuine repair actually look and feel like in practice. I want people who have never been modelled healthy love to experience, possibly for the first time, what secure love actually feels like in the body and not just in theory. Content is the fastest path to the scale that makes that possible, and I believe that with your help, packaged in a way that is compelling and culturally resonant, this is genuinely achievable.\n\nThe goal is one million engaged followers within the year, though any growth along the way will be celebrated because this is just the beginning. I want people who stop scrolling because something I said named an experience they have never heard named before, who share it with their partner at midnight, and who come back because the content keeps delivering that. The research is the engine behind this because it is genuinely original. Nobody in this space is talking about the way your social network shapes the quality of your relationship from the outside in. That idea is counterintuitive, deeply human, and backed by doctoral research from Oxford, and there is a whole body of social science, neuroscience, and relationship psychology behind it that has never been brought to a mainstream audience in this way.\n\nMy vision is for The Secure Love Lab™ to become the destination people find when they desperately need accessible, live support to practise these skills in a safe and contained community led by a credible, trauma-informed relationship expert. I want my name to become synonymous with the most credible, most accessible, and most research-grounded voice in this space. I want the Lab running at full capacity with a waitlist, The SECURE Method™ to become a clinically trusted framework that changes the way people experience love, a book, a keynote stage, and a media presence that extends the reach of this work far beyond any single platform. And eventually, I want the kind of cultural reach where a couples therapist in Cape Town, a family in London, or two people arguing in a car somewhere in the middle of Texas are using language that came from this work, even if they will never know where it came from.\n\nI would love to know what you think it would take to get there together."},{"label":"Anything else we should know?","value":"I have spent most of my career sitting with people in the hardest moments of their most important relationships. In inpatient wards in South Africa, in trauma clinics in London, in rooms where couples were barely speaking and families were falling apart. What struck me, again and again, was not how broken people were but how little they had been given. Not a deficit of love. A deficit of skills. Nobody had ever taught them how to stay regulated when the person they loved most triggered every protective response in their nervous system. Nobody had shown them what repair actually looks like, or how to return to each other after rupture without resentment quietly taking root.\n\nThat observation became a doctoral research question, and eventually a method, and eventually a mission.\n\nI hold a PhD in Psychology from the Universities of Oxford and Cape Town and work as a therapist at Khiron Clinics, one of the world''s leading trauma recovery centres. My clinical career spans South African inpatient care, UK day-clinic programmes, and the Woodfield Trauma Service in London, and I work with adults, couples, and families navigating developmental and relational trauma, attachment injuries, high-conflict patterns, dissociation, intimacy challenges, and burnout. My approach weaves together Acceptance and Commitment Therapy, Internal Family Systems, Emotionally Focused Therapy, polyvagal-informed practice, and somatic co-regulation, not as separate tools but as a coherent, integrated way of working with the whole person and the whole relationship system.\n\nMy doctoral research, published in the Journal of Prevention Science, followed something I kept noticing in clinical work: the people my clients turned to when their relationships got hard were shaping their behaviour in those relationships far more than anyone acknowledged. By teaching parents and partners to become more attuned to the people closest to them, and tracking how those changes rippled outward through communities, the research revealed something the field has largely overlooked. Who you talk to about your relationship determines how you show up in it. The people who love you most will, without meaning any harm, take your side, validate your feelings, and quietly reinforce the very patterns that are eroding your relationship over time. Teaching the people in your circle to advocate for the relationship rather than just for you is one of the most powerful and most underused interventions available to couples, and it is something no one else in this field is doing.\n\nThis is the foundation of The SECURE Method™ and The Secure Love Lab™, the live membership community where the method is taught, practised, and lived alongside others doing the same work. My focus has always been the same: reduce reactivity, restore safety and trust, and deliver change that endures long after the work together ends."}]'::jsonb, 'notion-legacy', '2026-04-17T11:52:00.000Z')
