values ('287bcb82c4bf81f9a1cefddeac5b7811', 'roccopiazza', 'Rocco', 'Piazza', 'drpiazza@thepiazzacenter.com', '5122034776', 'October 9, 2025 4:27', '[{"label":"Who will need to be included in communication about the work we’re doing?","value":"Executive Assistant Brandy Willis admin@thepiazzacenter.com She handles my calendar and my email. She schedules all my meetings and holds me accountable to meet deadlines.\n\nChief of Staff - Taylor Moreira - she oversees the entire clinical practice. She has a business management and marketing background. She leads, Manages, and holds accountable our entire team at The Piazza Center. Taylor@thepiazzacenter.com\n\nSocial Media Manager - Chelsea McCormack chelsea@thepiazzacenter.com\nShe handles @thepiazzacenter instagram/ FB/ YouTube/ Eblast efforts\n\nE-Commerce Manager- Brian Ellingwood brian@thepiazzacenter.com\n\nAccounting Contact: Alessandra Piazza, Payables — for invoices alessondra@thepiazzacenter.com"},{"label":"Who is your IDEAL target customer?","value":"Primary Target Audience — “The Health-Minded Modern Woman”\nDemographics\nAge: 32–52\nGender: Female\nLocation: Central Texas — Austin and surrounding suburbs (Westlake, Bee Cave, Lakeway, Dripping Springs, Tarrytown, Steiner Ranch)\nIncome: $150K–$500K+ household income\nOccupation: Healthcare, tech, wellness, real estate, law, education, entrepreneurship\nMarital / Family status: Married or partnered; often mothers of 1–3 children (commonly “fit moms”)\nEducation: College-educated or higher\nInsurance / financial behavior: Pays out of pocket; seeks value, not discounts\nPsychographics (Mindset & Values)\nLeads with health first — values safety, recovery, and minimal systemic impact.\nBody-aware — works out regularly, eats clean, focuses on longevity and wellness.\nSees surgery as a personal, empowering, restorative decision, not cosmetic vanity.\nPrefers natural, balanced proportions that align with their active lifestyle.\nDislikes “obvious” augmentation or overfilled looks.\nDesires low downtime to stay present for family, work, and exercise routines.\nValues education and trust — they research surgeons extensively before booking.\nFollows a “quiet luxury” aesthetic — refined, minimal, elegant.\nBehavioral Identifiers\nShops at: Lululemon, Alo Yoga, Vuori, Jenni Kayne, Goop, Whole Foods, The Tot\nFitness habits: Pilates, strength training, yoga, running, Orangetheory, spin\nFollows: wellness influencers (Dr. Will Cole, Melissa Wood-Tepperberg, The Class), longevity experts, and clean beauty advocates\nMedia: Podcasts like The Blonde Files, The Skinny Confidential, Huberman Lab, We Can Do Hard Things\nSupplements: collagen, adaptogens, greens, peptides (BPC-157, NAD+), functional mushrooms (Stamets 7)\nUses skincare: medical-grade lines like SkinBetter, Alastin, ZO, IS Clinical\nTravel: wellness retreats, beach destinations, boutique hotels (Auberge, Miraval, Amangiri)\nCore Motivations\nTo feel confident and comfortable in her own skin again (post-babies or aging).\nTo have breasts that look natural and move naturally.\nTo achieve harmony — not attention.\nTo maintain her fitness and vitality without interruption.\nTo choose the safest, most biocompatible implant (Motiva resonates deeply here).\nTo avoid complications like animation or distortion from older submuscular techniques.\nKey Messaging Angles\n“A modern, health-forward approach to breast enhancement.”\n“Designed for women who want to look and feel like the best version of themselves.”\n“Natural results that honor your body, your health, and your lifestyle.”\n“Confidence that moves with you.”\n“Science-backed implants with the lowest inflammatory profile.”\n\n\nSecondary Target Audience — “The Revision & Restoration Patient”\nDemographics\nAge: 38–60\nLocation: Austin metro and regional Texas (many travel for revisions)\nIncome: $175K–$400K+\nBackground: Previously had augmentation 10–20 years ago with older techniques\nPsychographics\nFeels disconnected from her body due to changes over time or poor previous results.\nNow prioritizes natural proportion, softness, and comfort over size.\nFeels frustrated with animation deformity or unnatural upper pole fullness.\nSeeks a surgeon who can fix rather than “just replace.”\nDeeply values trust, expertise, and a calm, reassuring environment.\nMotivations\n“I just want to feel natural and comfortable again.”\n“I want smaller, softer, more proportionate breasts.”\n“I want a surgeon who understands health, not just aesthetics.”\nMessaging Angles\n“Restore balance with today’s most advanced techniques.”\n“From overdone to natural — revision done right.”\n“Gentle, modern solutions for women who deserve comfort and confidence.”\n\n\nTertiary Audience — “The Preventative, Wellness-Oriented Woman”\n(Considering enhancement but not yet committed)\nDemographics\nAge: 28–40\nHealth, wellness, and beauty conscious\nEarly-stage moms or fitness enthusiasts exploring subtle aesthetic enhancement\nPsychographics\nResearches heavily before committing.\nValues prevention, bioharmony, and a “clean” approach to aesthetics.\nEngages with wellness education content (podcasts, YouTube, Instagram).\nMotivations\nWants subtle, long-term results with minimal biological footprint.\nFeels drawn to trusted, doctor-led education on safety and innovation.\nMessaging Angles\n“Empower your confidence — naturally.”\n“Breast enhancement designed for the health-first woman.”\n“Because confidence and wellness belong together.”"},{"label":"Do you have any brand identity or guidelines that you have available for reference? If so, please share the link below","value":"Yes. I can email this to hello@"},{"label":"What are the PAIN points of the customers you help?","value":"The Piazza Center Breast Surgery Audience: Pain Points, Psychology, and Positioning\n\n1. “I don’t feel seen, heard, or understood.”\nPain Point:\nThey’ve had experiences where plastic surgeons and their teams were dismissive, rushed, or focused on selling procedures rather than listening to their goals.\nDeeper Psychology:\nThey crave empathy, transparency, and a personalized plan that aligns with their body, values, and lifestyle.\nPositioning Opportunity:\n“We listen before we recommend. Every result begins with understanding who you are and how you live.”\nTone for Messaging:\nWarm, patient, intelligent, and collaborative — never transactional or salesy.\n\n2. “There’s too much misinformation — who can I trust?”\nPain Point:\nConflicting online advice, influencers, and marketing overload make it hard to discern truth from hype.\nDeeper Psychology:\nThey feel overwhelmed by noise but are willing to invest in trusted medical leadership.\nPositioning Opportunity:\n“Education first. Always.”\n“A science-driven approach that replaces hype with honesty.”\nTone for Messaging:\nEducational, calm, and authoritative. “Let us simplify what matters most to your body and your health.”\n\n3. “I’m scared about breast implant illness — are implants even safe?”\nPain Point:\nThey’ve internalized fear from social media and anecdotal stories that all implants are unsafe.\nDeeper Psychology:\nThey want reassurance through evidence, not dismissal. They respect doctors who acknowledge nuance.\nPositioning Opportunity:\n“Safety isn’t one-size-fits-all. That’s why we use Motiva — a next-generation, biocompatible implant designed for your body’s natural balance.”\nTone for Messaging:\nBalanced and science-forward — validate their concern, then educate gently.\n\n4. “I thought under the muscle was the best option — everyone does it.”\nPain Point:\nOutdated information from influencers, friends, and surgeons has perpetuated myths about implant placement.\nDeeper Psychology:\nThey want to make an informed decision that’s aligned with modern innovation, not outdated trends.\nPositioning Opportunity:\n“What was once standard isn’t always what’s best today. Muscle-sparing placement offers natural movement, faster recovery, and long-term comfort.”\nTone for Messaging:\nConfidently educational — modern yet nonjudgmental. “Here’s what’s changed — and why it matters for your body.”\n\n5. “I don’t want my breasts to be the first thing people notice.”\nPain Point:\nThey fear looking “done,” overfilled, or artificial — especially in health and professional environments.\nDeeper Psychology:\nTheir goal is internal harmony and self-confidence, not external validation.\nPositioning Opportunity:\n“Our philosophy: refined, natural results that look like you — just restored.”\nTone for Messaging:\nSophisticated and subtle. “Natural confidence is the new statement.”\n\n6. “Everyone says to go bigger — but I want smaller, natural results.”\nPain Point:\nPeer pressure and outdated industry norms push them toward exaggerated results.\nDeeper Psychology:\nThey value restraint and refinement — they want a surgeon who honors that.\nPositioning Opportunity:\n“Smaller, softer, proportionate — because confidence doesn’t come from size; it comes from alignment.”\nTone for Messaging:\nReassuring, affirming, feminine strength.\n\n7. “I didn’t know natural results were possible for me.”\nPain Point:\nThey’ve seen few real-life examples of natural breast results or assume they must choose between natural and “noticeable.”\nDeeper Psychology:\nThey want proof — visuals and testimonials that align with their aesthetic taste.\nPositioning Opportunity:\n“Natural is possible — and it’s what we do best.”\n“Modern techniques, soft-touch implants, and expert artistry create results that move with your body.”\nTone for Messaging:\nConfident, elegant, visually supported (before/after storytelling, patient testimonials).\n\n8. “I can’t afford to be out of commission — I have a family, fitness routine, and a career.”\nPain Point:\nThey associate surgery with long, painful recoveries incompatible with their lifestyle.\nDeeper Psychology:\nThey are efficient, active, and value vitality; recovery anxiety is often what delays their decision.\nPositioning Opportunity:\n“Little downtime. Major quality of life improvement.”\n“Our modern, gentle approach is designed for the woman who doesn’t slow down.”\nTone for Messaging:\nEmpowering, energetic, lifestyle-oriented. Show patient experiences emphasizing quick, easy recovery and return to fitness.\n\nCore Emotional Drivers\nAcross all pain points, the consistent emotional themes are:\nDesire for trust and education in an oversaturated market.\nDesire for health alignment and safety.\nDesire for natural confidence over external validation.\nDesire for low disruption to their high-functioning lifestyle.\nDesire for being seen and understood as more than a “cosmetic patient.”"},{"label":"What are the DESIRED OUTCOMES of the customers you help?","value":"Desired Outcomes for The Piazza Center Breast Surgery Patient\n\n1. Physical Outcomes — “Natural, Balanced, Functional Beauty”\nThese women desire results that enhance their form while maintaining function and health.\nNatural, proportionate breasts that align with their body shape and movement\nSoft, subtle, and refined results — not round, rigid, or “augmented” in appearance\nSymmetry and proportion that restore balance to their overall silhouette\nBreasts that move naturally — with or without muscle involvement\nLight, comfortable results (not heavy, tight, or limiting movement)\nMinimal scarring and short recovery time\nImplants that feel safe and biocompatible, with low inflammatory impact (Motiva emphasis)\nDurability and longevity — peace of mind that results will age gracefully\nIn essence: They want their breasts to look, feel, and move as if they’ve always been that way — only better.\n\n2. Emotional Outcomes — “Empowered, Comfortable, and Authentic”\nThe emotional journey is the real transformation for this audience.\nTo feel at home in their body again — especially after children or life changes\nTo restore confidence in how clothes fit, how they move, and how they see themselves\nTo feel feminine and strong, not objectified\nTo feel in control of their health and choices, rather than confused or pressured\nTo feel validated and heard by a team that truly listens\nTo release fear or shame around having surgery\nTo feel at peace with their decision — knowing it aligns with their health values\nIn essence: They want to feel more like themselves — not “transformed,” but restored.\n\n3. Experiential Outcomes — “Trust, Ease, and Elevated Care”\nThis is about the journey — how they feel before, during, and after their experience with your team.\nTo experience a thoughtful, calm, and unhurried consultation where they are genuinely seen\nTo feel educated and empowered, not sold to\nTo have a smooth, efficient process with minimal downtime and no surprises\nTo trust they’re receiving the most advanced, safest, modern approach\nTo feel supported by the entire team — from first call to final follow-up\nTo have a sense of belonging in a refined, wellness-centered environment\nTo walk away saying, “That was one of the best decisions I’ve ever made for myself.”\nIn essence: They want a medical experience that feels luxurious, human, and deeply intentional.\n\nSummary Statement:\n“Our patients desire natural, proportionate results that restore confidence and harmony with their bodies — achieved through the safest, most modern techniques and a patient experience defined by trust, empathy, and elevated care. They want to look and feel like themselves again — only more confident, more aligned, and more at peace.”"},{"label":"What is your PROCESS for helping clients get from where they are to where they want to go?","value":"YouTube Video: https://youtu.be/KB0WxQmBUro?si=8bn_GFsH8C6eGG7U\nWe need to get you this questionnaire to look at."},{"label":"Please provide links to some examples of social media clips that you like from a design perspective","value":"Like: (i need to get this pulled toghether for you.)\n\nDon’t like: https://www.instagram.com/reel/DOypn1IiTxA/?igsh=M2xvYTdvdTRieDJr"},{"label":"Please provide links to video thumbnails/cover images that you like from a design perspective","value":"Recent content from The Piazza Center instagram i like that is consistent with social media guidelines"},{"label":"What font preferences do you have or would you like to see in your designs? If you are open to our recommendations, please feel free to mention it below","value":"see guidelines"},{"label":"What color preferences do you have or would you like to see in your designs?","value":"see guidelines"},{"label":"Google Drive Link to pictures of yourself","value":"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fo/kqa0d2huvg8k90vcsn4xg/AABBF5zVDqbl-y23GxWEdy0?rlkey=kin5uf1yc7xx5ka7c4qf1em43&st=xvwds24u&dl=0"},{"label":"Google Doc Link to links to podcast, speeches or any other video content you want us to create content from","value":"https://youtu.be/mE6QYvirEmw"},{"label":"What would success look like working together?","value":"Open communication. Collaborative. Reciprocal."},{"label":"Anything else we should know?","value":"That’s it for now. Thank you so much for reviewing all of this!"}]'::jsonb, 'notion-legacy', '2025-10-09T04:27:00.000Z')
